                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 40.&#8212;<name type="person"
                                                key="619">Private Josiah Cheever</name>, <name
                                                type="organization" key="653">Co. B, 15th
                                        Vt.</name>, was admitted <date type="admit"
                                                when="1863-04-14">April 14, 1863</date>: Headache;
                                        occasional delirium; pulse 100, compressible; hot and dry
                                        skin; six to eight stools daily; short, dry cough; sibilant
                                        rhonchus distinct over chest anteriorly; abdomen tympanitic.
                                        Calomel, opium and ipecacuanha in small doses alternating
                                        with effervescing mixture ameliorated his condition. The
                                        chest and head symptoms subsided, but the abdomen remained
                                        distended and tender and the diarrh&#339;a continued. On
                                        the 22d his tongue became cracked and pulse feeble, 120. He
                                        died on the <date type="death" when="1863-04-28"
                                        >28th</date>, notwithstanding the administration of
                                        turpentine, alcoholic stimulants and ammonia. <hi
                                                rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination: Thoracic
                                        viscera normal. Mucous membrane of small intestine injected,
                                        lower ileum presenting eight large ulcers; corresponding
                                        mesenteric glands enlarged.&#8212;<hi rend="italic"
                                                  ><name type="hospital" key="189">Third Division
                                                  Hospital</name>, Alexandria, Va.</hi>
                                </p>
                        
